# {{lb|fr|linguistics|grammar}} {{ng|Refers to a descriptive word or phrase that modifies a nominal element without an intervening verb.}}
## [[attributive adjective]]
##: {{synonyms|fr|adjectif épithète}}
##: {{hyponyms|fr|adjectif épithète liée|épithète détachée}}
## [[noun adjunct]]
##: {{synonyms|fr|nom épithète}}
# [[epithet]] {{gloss|designating or qualifying term, label}}
#: {{coi|fr|l'épithète malsonnante de bon|the offensive '''epithet''' of good}}

====Usage notes====
* <ref>[https://dictionnaire.lerobert.com/guide/epithete Épithète] & [https://dictionnaire.lerobert.com/guide/adjectifs-qualificatifs-et-relationnels Adjectifs qualificatifs et relationnels''] in ''Le Robert Dico en ligne''</ref> A student of French who is familiar with English grammatical jargon should note that, despite their having the appearance of being perfect cognates of {{m|en|epithet}} and {{m|en|attributive adjective}}, the terms {{m|fr|épithète}} and {{m|fr|adjectif attribut}} are actually used for entirely different concepts:
** In English, an adjective that applies to or qualifies a noun directly, without need of a verb, is called an {{m|en|attributive adjective}}, but in French, this is called an {{m|fr|épithète}} (or {{m|fr|adjectif épithète}}, if context requires a greater level of specificity to differentiate from {{m|fr|nom épithète}} or locutions formed around other parts of speech and functioning in  adjectival capacity).
** Rather than referring to what is called an {{m|en|attributive adjective}} in English, the French term {{m|fr|adjectif attribut}} is used for an adjectival element whose link to a nominal is supported by an attributive (copulative) verb. In English grammar, these are called {{m|en|[[predicative adjective]]s}}.

====Derived terms====
